# Spring Boot Development Rules

## General Rules
- Always use Java 25 features and best practices for Spring Boot service development
- Follow Spring Boot conventions and patterns
- Use dependency injection properly
- Implement proper exception handling
- Use logging with SLF4J and Logback
- Follow REST API best practices
- Implement proper validation using Bean Validation
- Use Spring Security for authentication and authorization when needed

## Naming Conventions
- All class names, method names, and attribute names must be in English
- Use PascalCase for class names
- Use camelCase for method names and attributes
- Use UPPER_CASE for constants
- Package names should be lowercase and follow reverse domain naming (com.reservas.sistema_reservas)

## Documentation
- Every public method must have updated Javadoc documentation
- Include @param, @return, and @throws tags where applicable
- Document the purpose and behavior of classes and methods
- Keep documentation current with code changes

## DTOs (Data Transfer Objects)
- Use Java records for all DTO classes
- Records provide immutable data structures with automatic equals, hashCode, and toString
- Example: `public record UserDto(String name, String email) {}`
- Use records for request/response objects in REST controllers

